[[File:Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun zenkei.JPG|thumb|260px|right|{{center|Legendary Tomb (Udo no Haka) of Inishiki Irihiko no Mikoto}}{{small|({{ill|Osaka Prefecture|de|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|zh|Osaka Prefecture}}・{{ill|Sennan District|de|Sennan District|ja|泉南郡|zh|Sennan District}}・{{ill|Misaki Town|de|Misaki Town|ja|岬町|zh|Misaki Town}}の{{ill|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun|de|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun|ja|淡輪ニサンザイ古墳|zh|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun}}) }}]] '''Inishiki Irihiko no Mikoto''' (五十瓊敷入彦命{{Sfn|五十瓊敷入彦命（古代氏族）|2010年}}) was an ancient {{ill|Japanese Imperial family member|de|Japanese Imperial family member|ja|皇族|zh|Japanese Imperial family member}} known from the {{ill|Kiki|de|Kiki|ja|記紀|zh|Kiki}} texts.
In the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|de|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|zh|Nihon Shoki}}'', he is called “Inishiki Irihiko no Mikoto”, “Inishiki no Mikoto”, or “Inishiki Ōji”, and in the ''{{ill|Kojiki|de|Kojiki|ja|古事記|zh|Kojiki}}'' as '''Inshiki Irihiko no Mikoto'''.
He was a son of the 11th {{ill|Emperor Suinin|de|Emperor Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|zh|Emperor Suinin}} and the elder full brother of the 12th {{ill|Emperor Keikō|de|Emperor Keikō|ja|景行天皇|zh|Emperor Keikō}}. He is famous in the legends concerning the sacred treasures of {{ill|Isonokami Shrine|de|Isonokami Shrine|ja|石上神宮|zh|Isonokami Shrine}} in {{ill|Tenri|de|Tenri|ja|天理市|zh|Tenri}}.
== Genealogy == {{smaller|(Names follow ''Nihon Shoki'' first, with ''Kojiki'' names in parentheses)}}
According to both the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|de|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|zh|Nihon Shoki}}'' and the ''{{ill|Kojiki|de|Kojiki|ja|古事記|zh|Kojiki}}'', he was born to {{ill|Emperor Suinin|de|Emperor Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|zh|Emperor Suinin}} and the later Empress {{ill|Hibasu-hime no Mikoto|de|Hibasu-hime no Mikoto|ja|日葉酢媛命|zh|Hibasu-hime no Mikoto}}.
Inishiki Irihiko no Mikoto was the eldest, and the texts record four full siblings: * Younger brother: {{ill|Otari-hiko no Mikoto|de|Otari-hiko no Mikoto|ja|大足彦尊|zh|Otari-hiko no Mikoto}} – the 12th '''{{ill|Emperor Keikō|de|Emperor Keikō|ja|景行天皇|zh|Emperor Keikō}}'''. * Younger sister: {{ill|Ōnakatsu-hime no Mikoto|de|Ōnakatsu-hime no Mikoto|ja|大中姫命|zh|Ōnakatsu-hime no Mikoto}} (the ''Kojiki'' names the male {{ill|Ōnakatsu-hiko no Mikoto|de|Ōnakatsu-hiko no Mikoto|ja|大中津日子命|zh|Ōnakatsu-hiko no Mikoto}}). * Younger sister: {{ill|Yamato-hime no Mikoto|de|Yamato-hime no Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|zh|Yamato-hime no Mikoto}}. * Younger brother: {{ill|Wakaki Niiri-hiko no Mikoto|de|Wakaki Niiri-hiko no Mikoto|ja|稚城瓊入彦命|zh|Wakaki Niiri-hiko no Mikoto}}.
== Records == In the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|de|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|zh|Nihon Shoki}}'', the following deeds are recorded for Inishiki Irihiko no Mikoto{{Sfn|五十瓊敷入彦命（古代氏族）|2010年}}: * Year 30, January 6 of Emperor Suinin’s reign: ** When asked what they desired, Inishiki Irihiko no Mikoto chose bows and arrows, and Otari-hiko no Mikoto chose the throne. The emperor granted bows and arrows to Inishiki, and told Otari-hiko to succeed to the throne{{Sfn|五十瓊敷入彦命（古代氏族）|2010年}}. * Year 35, September: ** He was dispatched to {{ill|Kawachi Province|de|Kawachi Province|ja|河内国|zh|Kawachi Province}}, where he excavated {{ill|Takaishi Pond|de|Takaishi Pond|ja|高石池|zh|Takaishi Pond}} in {{ill|Takaishi|de|Takaishi|ja|高石市|zh|Takaishi}} and {{ill|Chinui Pond|de|Chinui Pond|ja|茅渟池|zh|Chinui Pond}} in {{ill|Izumisano|de|Izumisano|ja|泉佐野市|zh|Izumisano}}{{Sfn|五十瓊敷入彦命（古代氏族）|2010年}}. [[File:Isonokami-jingu, haiden-2.jpg|thumb|200px|right|{{ill|Isonokami Shrine|de|Isonokami Shrine|ja|石上神宮|zh|Isonokami Shrine}} in {{ill|Tenri|de|Tenri|ja|天理市|zh|Tenri}}]] * Year 39, October: ** At the {{ill|Upper Uto River Shrine|de|Upper Uto River Shrine|ja|菟砥川上宮|zh|Upper Uto River Shrine}} in the {{ill|Uto River basin|de|Uto River basin|ja|菟砥川流域|zh|Uto River basin}} (in {{ill|Hannan|de|Hannan|ja|阪南町|zh|Hannan}}, {{ill|Sennan District|de|Sennan District|ja|泉南郡|zh|Sennan District}}), he forged 1,000 swords and dedicated them to {{ill|Isonokami Shrine|de|Isonokami Shrine|ja|石上神宮|zh|Isonokami Shrine}}. From then on, he oversaw the shrine’s treasures{{Sfn|五十瓊敷入彦命（古代氏族）|2010年}}. ** An alternate account says he had 1,000 great swords forged, receiving ten crafts offices (品部): {{ill|Tatebe|de|Tatebe|ja|楯部|zh|Tatebe}}, {{ill|Worabe|de|Worabe|ja|倭文部|zh|Worabe}}, {{ill|Kamiyugebe|de|Kamiyugebe|ja|神弓削部|zh|Kamiyugebe}}, {{ill|Kamiyazukuri-be|de|Kamiyazukuri-be|ja|神矢作部|zh|Kamiyazukuri-be}}, {{ill|Ōanasobe|de|Ōanasobe|ja|大穴磯部|zh|Ōanasobe}}, {{ill|Tomashikibe|de|Tomashikibe|ja|泊橿部|zh|Tomashikibe}}, {{ill|Tamakurabe|de|Tamakurabe|ja|玉作部|zh|Tamakurabe}}, {{ill|Kamikōbe|de|Kamikōbe|ja|神刑部|zh|Kamikōbe}}, {{ill|Hiokibe|de|Hiokibe|ja|日置部|zh|Hiokibe}}, and {{ill|Ōtōhaibe|de|Ōtōhaibe|ja|大刀佩部|zh|Ōtōhaibe}}. Those swords were moved from {{ill|Oshisaka Village|de|Oshisaka Village|ja|忍坂邑|zh|Oshisaka Village}} to {{ill|Isonokami Shrine|de|Isonokami Shrine|ja|石上神宮|zh|Isonokami Shrine}}{{Sfn|五十瓊敷入彦命（古代氏族）|2010年}}. * Year 87, February 5: ** Due to old age, he entrusted oversight of the shrine’s treasures to his sister {{ill|Ōnakatsu-hime no Mikoto|de|Ōnakatsu-hime no Mikoto|ja|大中姫命|zh|Ōnakatsu-hime no Mikoto}}. She, citing her delicate health, passed them to {{ill|Mononobe no Tokotsune|de|Mononobe no Tokotsune|ja|物部十千根|zh|Mononobe no Tokotsune}}, establishing the Mononobe clan’s stewardship{{Sfn|五十瓊敷入彦命（古代氏族）|2010年}}.
In the ''{{ill|Kojiki|de|Kojiki|ja|古事記|zh|Kojiki}}'' entry for Emperor Suinin, he is credited with creating {{ill|Chinui Pond|de|Chinui Pond|ja|茅渟池|zh|Chinui Pond}}, {{ill|Sayama Pond|de|Sayama Pond|ja|狭山池|zh|Sayama Pond}} in {{ill|Osakasayama|de|Osakasayama|ja|大阪狭山市|zh|Osakasayama}}, and a pond at {{ill|Kusaka|de|Kusaka|ja|日下|zh|Kusaka}}, and with forging 1,000 swords at {{ill|Tottori River Upper Shrine|de|Tottori River Upper Shrine|ja|鳥取河上宮|zh|Tottori River Upper Shrine}} for {{ill|Isonokami Shrine|de|Isonokami Shrine|ja|石上神宮|zh|Isonokami Shrine}}. He also organized the Kawakami tribe there{{Sfn|五十瓊敷入彦命（古代氏族）|2010年}}.
== Tomb == [[File:Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun haisho-1.JPG|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Udo no Haka (宇度墓), the tomb of Inishiki Irihiko no Mikoto at {{ill|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun|de|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun|ja|淡輪ニサンザイ古墳|zh|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun}}, {{ill|Misaki Town|de|Misaki Town|ja|岬町|zh|Misaki Town}}}}]] The tomb, designated by the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|de|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|zh|Imperial Household Agency}}, is the '''Udo no Haka''' (宇度墓, {{Coord|34|19|49.67|N|135|10|43.49|E|region:JP-27|name=Udo no Haka (Inishiki Irihiko no Mikoto’s tomb)}}) in {{ill|Tannowa|de|Tannowa|ja|淡輪|zh|Tannowa}}, {{ill|Misaki Town|de|Misaki Town|ja|岬町|zh|Misaki Town}}, {{ill|Sennan District|de|Sennan District|ja|泉南郡|zh|Sennan District}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|de|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|zh|Osaka Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|keyhole-shaped tumulus|de|keyhole-shaped tumulus|ja|前方後円墳|zh|keyhole-shaped tumulus}} called {{ill|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun|de|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun|ja|淡輪ニサンザイ古墳|zh|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun}}, 200 m long.
Although not mentioned in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|de|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|zh|Nihon Shoki}}'' or ''{{ill|Kojiki|de|Kojiki|ja|古事記|zh|Kojiki}}'', the ''{{ill|Engishiki|de|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|zh|Engishiki}}'' (927) lists “Udo no Haka” in {{ill|Izumi Province|de|Izumi Province|ja|和泉国|zh|Izumi Province}}, {{ill|Hine District|de|Hine District|ja|日根郡|zh|Hine District}}, with precincts of 3 chō east–west by 3 chō north–south, guarded by 3 households, classed as a remote tomb. An earlier 691 decree established three guard households at royal tombs of merit; scholars suggest this reflects parallel tomb-designations based on older records like the ''{{ill|Teiki|de|Teiki|ja|帝紀|zh|Teiki}}'' and ''{{ill|Kyuji|de|Kyuji|ja|旧辞|zh|Kyuji}}''. One theory holds that the tombs of {{ill|Yamato Takeru|de|Yamato Takeru|ja|ヤマトタケル|zh|Yamato Takeru}}, {{ill|Hikoisosenu no Mikoto|de|Hikoisosenu no Mikoto|ja|彦五瀬命|zh|Hikoisosenu no Mikoto}}, Inishiki Irihiko no Mikoto, and {{ill|Todo Chikarako|de|Todo Chikarako|ja|菟道稚郎子|zh|Todo Chikarako}} formed the four boundaries of {{ill|Yamato Province|de|Yamato Province|ja|大和国|zh|Yamato Province}}<ref>{{Harvid|仁藤}}</ref>.
The tomb fell into ruin in the medieval period{{Sfn|宇度墓（国史）}}. In 1874, based on the ''{{ill|Senshūshi|de|Senshūshi|ja|泉州志|zh|Senshūshi}}'', it was located on Mt. Tamada, but in 1880 moved to the present site{{Sfn|宇度墓（国史）}}. The ''{{ill|Izumiki|de|Izumiki|ja|和泉志|zh|Izumiki}}'' records it as the tomb of {{ill|Ki no Koyumi|de|Ki no Koyumi|ja|紀小弓|zh|Ki no Koyumi}}{{Sfn|宇度墓（国史）}}.
== Legends == According to the shrine legend of {{ill|Inaba Shrine|de|Inaba Shrine|ja|伊奈波神社|zh|Inaba Shrine}} in {{ill|Gifu City|de|Gifu City|ja|岐阜市|zh|Gifu City}}, Inishiki Irihiko no Mikoto pacified Ōshū by imperial order, but Murō no Kami {{ill|Toyomasa|de|Toyomasa|ja|豊益|zh|Toyomasa}}, envious of his success, slandered him as rebellious. He was then attacked as a traitor and killed there. His consort, {{ill|Nunoshi-hime no Mikoto|de|Nunoshi-hime no Mikoto|ja|渟熨斗姫命|zh|Nunoshi-hime no Mikoto}}, daughter of Emperor Keikō, left the capital to mourn him here until her death.
